messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path for the endpoint (as implemented in the code): /printshops/{printShopID}/employees

- All HTTP methods acceptable for this path? No

- HEAD: Yes ( HEAD requests are handled by Spring for endpoints that have a GET mapping on the same path; since there is a GET mapping for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees, HEAD is effectively supported)

- POST: Yes (implemented as addEmployee for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees)

- OPTIONS: Yes (Spring MVC automatically responds to OPTIONS for defined mappings, listing allowed methods)

- TRACE: No (no TRACE mapping is defined for this path)

- GET: Yes (implemented as getEmployees for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees)

- PUT: Yes (implemented as editEmployee for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees)

- DELETE: No (DELETE mapping exists for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID}, not for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees)

- PATCH: No (no PATCH mapping defined for this path)

Explanation:
- The editEmployee method is mapped with @RequestMapping(value = "/printshops/{printShopID}/employees", method = RequestMethod.PUT), so PUT on /printshops/{printShopID}/employees is supported.
- The same path is also used by getEmployees (GET) and addEmployee (POST) in the same controller, so GET and POST are supported for that path as well.
- There is no explicit HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PATCH mappings for this specific path, but HEAD is typically handled by Spring for GET-enabled endpoints, and OPTIONS is provided automatically for mapped endpoints. TRACE and PATCH are not implemented for this path.
- DELETE is only defined for the path /printshops/{printShopID}/employees/{employeeID}, not for /printshops/{printShopID}/employees, so DELETE is not acceptable for this endpoint path.
